      <hedline>
        <hl1>Checking the Tests</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jonathan Reinhardt letter calls for reconsideration of No Child Left Behind Act rather than increased oversight (March 18 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Testing Errors Prompt Calls for Oversight'' (front page, March 18):</p>
        <p>Perhaps the solution lies not in oversight, but in reconsidering the effectiveness of the No Child Left Behind law and the practice of over-testing.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Testing Errors Prompt Calls for Oversight'' (front page, March 18):</p>
        <p>Perhaps the solution lies not in oversight, but in reconsidering the effectiveness of the No Child Left Behind law and the practice of over-testing.</p>
        <p>Across the country, schools have dumped curriculums that teach creativity, group work and problem-solving because they cannot be measured according to standards.</p>
        <p>So instead of a generation of innovators who can think outside the box and compete globally, we will have a uniform generation that will be good at taking tests.</p>
        <p>Thank goodness for colleges like Mount Holyoke and a growing number of others that are realizing that standardized test scores are, in fact, dispensable.</p>
        <p>Jonathon Reinhardt  State College, Pa.  March 18, 2006</p>
      </block>
